    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Signs in Belgium</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rudolph Pick letter on May 21 What's Doing In travel article on Brussels notes confusion that results because road signs are printed in both French and Flemish (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor: ''What's Doing in Brussels'' (May 21) prompts me to alert Americans to a problem they face when driving in Belgium.</p>
        <p>We lived in Holland and often traveled via Antwerp to Brussels. But my nonlinguist friends who did this usually could not find their way back. They circled the ring road around Brussels for an hour looking in vain for a sign reading ''Antwerp'' or ''Nederland'' (Netherland). Why?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor: ''What's Doing in Brussels'' (May 21) prompts me to alert Americans to a problem they face when driving in Belgium.</p>
        <p>We lived in Holland and often traveled via Antwerp to Brussels. But my nonlinguist friends who did this usually could not find their way back. They circled the ring road around Brussels for an hour looking in vain for a sign reading ''Antwerp'' or ''Nederland'' (Netherland). Why?</p>
        <p>Belgium is a bilingual country; public notices are posted in both languages, but road signs are only in French or Flemish. Finally my friends were told by a good Samaritan to look for the sign ''Anvers'' (Antwerp) or ''Pays-Bas'' (French for Netherlands). The same problem exists in Flemish-speaking areas: road signs like ''Luik'' and ''Rijssel'' refer to Liege and Lille!</p>
        <p>My advice is to get a good road map that gives both the French and the Flemish names of the towns.</p>
        <p>RUDOLPH PICK  Pompano Beach, Fla.</p>
      </block>
